    'There are different types of chemical reactions occurring around us or being carried out for the benefit of mankind, e.g. combination reactions, decomposition reactions, displacement reactions, precipitation reactions, reduction-oxidation (redox) reactions, photochemical reactions etc. \newline
Now answer the following questions:

\begin{enumerate}[label=\roman*)]
    \item Combustion of coke is a combination reaction. $\mathrm{CO}_2$ is not a pollutant. Then why is combustion of coke harmful?
    \item Which reaction followed by two combination reactions are involved in white wash of walls?
    \item Give one use of tin plating in daily life.
    \item How photochemical reactions have played an important role in photography?
\end{enumerate}


% =============================================================
%Question End
% =============================================================',
    NULL,
    '\begin{enumerate}[label=\roman*)]
    \item $\mathrm{CO}_2$ is not considered a pollutant up to a certain level. Rather, it helps in maintaining the temperature of the Earth. Combustion of coke is harmful as it increases the concentration of $\mathrm{CO}_2$ in the atmosphere which causes global warming due to the greenhouse effect.
    \item The reaction of calcium with oxygen gives quicklime $(\mathrm{CaO})$ which when mixed with water forms slaked lime $\mathrm{Ca}(\mathrm{OH})_2$ [combination reaction] and when slaked lime is applied on walls then it reacts with $\mathrm{CO}_2$ of the air to form $\mathrm{CaCO}_3$.
    % Diagram Begins
    \begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{SV_CBSE10_CHT_01.Chemical Reactions and Equations_1_3.PNG}
    \end{center}
    % Diagram Ends
    \item Tin-plating is preferred in the tiffin boxes because tin is non-poisonous and hence, does not contaminate the food kept in them.
    \item A photographic film used in black and white photography is a celluloid film coated with silver chloride. The silver chloride decomposes in the presence of sunlight and its working is totally based on this decomposition reaction giving silver which forms the image on the film.
    % Diagram Begins
    \begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{SV_CBSE10_CHT_01.Chemical Reactions and Equations_1_4.PNG}
    \end{center}
    % Diagram Ends
\end{enumerate}',
    '',
